Swimming migrant. Along the coast, N-S [6]. Refuge. Unclear, but some movements seem directed at areas of concentrated food available [17]. Retreat from the ice front. Possible connection to their molting behavior [16]. Instigated by photoperiod [533]. Groups seem to migrate together [17]. Not all groups migrate, for instance those in Cook Inlet, St. Lawrence estuary and maybe Cumberland Sound [33]. Particularly fast and coordinated movement north in August. Consistency of migrations noted [17]. Warm freshwater during migration may be related to beluga molting [16]. Consistent schedule [33].

Different summering ground populations may be functionally isolated [20].

Found in palm groves. Seems to roost singly [436]. Insectivore [436].

Flying migrant. Patterns unclear [100]. Unknown motivation. Some individuals may be year-round residents [100]. Northern populations known to migrate. Roosts in trees. Sex segregation for most of year. Seasonal breeding: mate in autumn and winter, litters of 2-4 in May and June [100]. Insectivore [100].
Solitary. Roosts in foliage [437]. Insectivore [437].
Insectivore [438].

Unclear movement, possible N-S migration [100, 3662]. Active year-round. Southward winter shift reported. Roost on moss, in trees and caves. Seasonal reproduction: mate in autumn, litters of 1-4 in May-June [100]. "frequently join groups of migratory birds" [3662]. Insectivore [100].
Solitary [439], probably migratory with sex-segregated summer ranges (taxonomic confusion) [190]. Insectivore [439].

Unclear movement [440]. Some individuals may be year-round residents, even in the north of the range [440]. May be migratory. Does not hibernate. Roosts in trees. Seasonal breeding [440]. Insectivore [440].
Roosts in house roofs, probably under bark. East Africa: breed twice per year during the rainy seasons [102]. Insectivore [102].

Common name: Little Bent-winged Bat, Little Long-fingered Bat
Notes: Unclear movement. Australia: females to nursery roosts. Up to 200 km, usually shorter distances [134]. Roosts in caves, usually individually except during breeding: nursery roosts. [219]. Cave dependent [243]. Distinct winter and maternity roost caves [134]. Insectivore [161].
Unclear movement, probable cave switching, but unknown extent [102]. Cave dependent. Probably distinct winter hibernacula caves and summer maternity roost caves. Seasonal breeding [102].

Flying migrant, extent and patterns unclear [455, 208]. Unknown motivation. Roosts in caves [200], sometimes buildings or trees [208], but seemingly cave dependent, large warm caves [455]. Northern populations hibernate in cool caves. Some populations may migrate [208]. Insectivore [455].
Hibernate [102].
Roosts in caves, cave dependent [243].

Common name: Large Bent-winged Bat, Western Bent-winged Bat
Notes: Roosts in caves [200], cave dependent [243]. Insectivore [200].
Roosts in caves, cave dependent [167]. Insectivore [167].

Common name: Manavil Long-fingered Bat, Manavi Long-fingered Bat
Notes: Roosts in caves. Seemingly seasonal breeding [167]. Insectivore [167].

Common name: Intermediate Long-fingered Bat, Medium Bent-winged Bat
Notes: Roosts in caves [200], cave dependent [243].

Flying migrant, up to 150 km. Females migrate between maternity roosts and hibernacula [102]. Refuge [102]. Hibernacula caves [102]. Cave dependent. Distinct caves for hibernacula and summer maternity roosts. Hibernacula usually cooler and at higher elevations. Seasonal breeding [102]. Insectivore [102].
Found roosting in large numbers in a cave [457].

Flying migrant. Female congregation and dispersal around nursery caves. Up to several hundred km [134]. Refuge/ breeding [134]? Suitable nursery roosts, warm humid [134]. Male movements unclear [134]. Cave dependent. torpor in winter to survive with low food. Distinct winter and nursery caves. Southeastern  bats hibernate in the winter due to lack of insects. Maternity colonies form in warm humid caves. Northern bats may exhibit different behavior due to available caves [134, 454]. Insectivore [134].
Thought to roost in caves [458].

Common name: Nicobar Long-fingered Bat, Small Bent-winged Bat, Small Long-fingered Bat
Notes: Known to roost in caves [200]. Insectivore [208].

Common name: Common Bentwing Bat, Schreiber's Bent-winged Bat, Schreiber's Long-fingered Bat
Notes: Flying migrant, Average 40-100 km. Longest three distances 422-833 km [288, 250]. Appears to be cave dispersal and re-congregation [250]. Refuge [288]. Suitably winter caves [288, 250]. Some caves used year-round [288]. Roosts in caves, also mines, cellars, underground locations. Nursery colonies, males and non-reproductive females roost elsewhere in same/nearby cave. Some caves used year-round, others only seasonally. Hibernate [288]. Insectivore [288].
Unclear movement [460]. Few records below 50 m thought to possibly be breeding colonies and thus evidence of altitudinal migration [460, 458].

Common name: Great Bent-winged Bat, Greater Bent-winged Bat, Great Long-fingered Bat
Notes: Roosts in caves, cave dependent [243].

Common name: Little Tube-nosed Bat, Tibetan Tube-nosed Bat
Notes: May roost in foliage, not caves [208, 420]. Thought to hibernate [420].
Roost in foliage, also caves and rock shelters [208].
Roost in trees: leaves, nests, etc. Seasonal breeding. Maternity roosts unknown [134]. Insectivore [161]. Also nectarivore [134].
May hibernate [208].

Common name: Greater Tube-nosed Bat, Hilgendorf's Tube-nosed Bat
Hutton's Tube-nosed Bat, White-bellied Tube-nosed Bat
Greater Tube-nosed Bat, Rufous Tube-nosed Bat
Notes: Roosts in caves, trees, and houses [208]. Insectivore [420].

Common name: Taiwanese Tube-nosed Bat, Taiwan Tube-nosed Bat

Notes: Roost in tree hollows [461].

Common name: Brown Tube-nosed Bat, Lesser Tube-nosed Bat
Gloomy Tube-nosed Bat, Tsushima Tube-nosed Bat

Notes: Found roosting in a tree [420]. Hibernates [132].

Common name: Grey Large-footed Bat, Large-footed Bat, Large-footed Mouse-eared Bat, Large-footed Myotis
Notes: Taiwan: roosts in caves and tunnels [208]. Indopacific islands: roost in caves [161]. Australis: roost in caves and tunnels, also foliage. Tropical females have three births/ year [243]. Insectivore, also piscivore [208, 161].
Roosts in buildings, caves, hollow trees and logs, among rocks [356, 191]. Up; to three births per year. Thought not to hibernate. [191]. Insectivore, piscivore [356].

Common name: Alcathoe Myotis, ALCATHOE MYOTIS, Alcathoe Whiskered Bat, ALCATHOE WHISKERED BAT
Notes: Unclear movement [288]. Possible refuge migration between roosts or  tracking migration to swarming caves [288]. Summer roosts: cracks in trees, behind bark. Swarming caves (mid-August). Winter roost cave. Seasonal breeding, nursery roosts [288]. Insectivore [288].
Thailand: found in limestone cave [200]. Found in caves [208].
Thought to  roost in rocks crevices and limestone caves [200].
Insectivore [470].

Common name: Steppe Whiskered Bat, STEPPE WHISKERED BAT
Notes: Unclear movement [417]. Roosts in rock crevices and cracks. Winter roosts in caves [417]. Insectivore [288].
Flying migrant. Altitudinal migration [100]. Refuge [100]. Roosts in caves. Hibernation roosts unknown  [100]. Insectivore [100].

Non-migratory [100], Migratory [3655]. Refuge? [3655]. Roosts in caves. Hibernates for winter in the northern part of range. In the south, changes roosts (distance unknown) and active some of the time [100], form nursery colonies in mid-March and "most individuals leave the caves in winter and congregate in protected places, usually over water." (p71) [3655]. Insectivore [100].

Common name: Bechstein's Bat, Bechstein's Myotis, Bechstein's Myotis
Notes: Non-migratory [250, 288]. Frequent movements on a local scale, no significant migration. Winter and summer roosts are generally <10 km. Max recorded movement 73 km [250]. Nursery roosts, seasonal breeding. Roost changes every few days. Mostly solitary [288]. Insectivore [288].

Common name: Lesser Mouse-eared Bat, Lesser Mouse-eared Myotis, LESSER MOUSE-EARED MYOTIS
Notes: Flying migrant, extent unclear [420]. Unknown motivation. Roost in attics, caves, sometimes tree holes [208, 420]. Populations in Iran and Arabia migrate. Iran: sex-segregation during breeding season [420]. Insectivore [208].
West Africa: Roost in banana leaves [102]. Insectivore [102].
Unclear movement [208]. Roosts in caves. May be migratory [208].

Flying migrant, extent unclear [208], probably short-distance, mostly < 40 km, two max 308 km, 618 km [288, 250]. Refuge [288]. Suitable winter roosts (caves) [288]. Maternity colonies found in buildings. Winter roosts in caves, tunnels, cellars, mine shafts. Northern populations hibernate. Some populations partially migratory [208]. Summer roosts: trees, building cracks. Winter roosts in caves and mines. Nursery colonies, seasonal breeding [288]. Insectivore [208, 288].
Found in caves [464].

Non-migratory [100]. Roosts in caves, mines, buildings. Also rocky outcrops, trees, and group in warm months. Hibernates and high latitudes and altitudes, known to be active even below freezing. Seasonal breeding [100, 356]. Insectivore [100].

Flying migrant, partial. ~100 km, max recorded 150 km in Balkan Peninsula. Cave congregation and dispersal. [288]. Common 40-50 km movements [250]. Refuge [288]. Suitable winter roosts [288]. Year-round presence in some caves [288]. Roost in caves and mines year-round. Hibernate in larger groups. Seasonal breeding. Movement between summer and winter roosts, extent not fully clear [288]. Insectivore (mostly aquatic), also piscivore [288].
Seasonal, highly synchronized breeding. Roosts in roofs, caves, crevices. Nursery colonies. Hibernate in small groups [190]. Insectivore [190].
Found near limestone caves [200]. Hibernates in caves [208].
Non-migratory [100]. Roosts in rocks, caves, mines, tree bark, old swallow nests, buildings. Hibernates for the winter. Seasonal breeding and molting [100]. Insectivore [100].

Common name: Csorbas Mouse-eared Bat, Csorbas Mouse-eared Myotis.

Notes: Flying migrant. Medium-range, 300 km in lowlands, max 350 in Belgium. Females may migrate farther than males. Possible altitudinal migration [288]. Refuge, sex-biased [288]. Suitable winter roosts [288]. Regions with both suitable winter and summer roosts are more sedentary [288]. Roost in caves, tunnels, buildings, hollow trees. May migrate between distinct seasonal roosts [208]. Nursery colonies, seasonal breeding. Summer roosts: roofs, tree holes, often in lowlands. Winter roosts: caves, mines, bunkers, cellars, often in low mountains. Females may migrate farther than males [288]. Insectivore (mostly aquatic) [208, 288].

Flying migrant, extent, patterns unclear [208]. Usually 100- 150 km [288, 250], max 304 km [288]. Refuge, sex-biased [208]. Suitable winter roosts [208, 288]. Some population move much less. Finland: <10 km [250]. Roosts in caves, mines, cellars, wells, near water. Hibernate. Summer roosts in tree holes, attics, steeples, under bridges [208]. Summer nursery colonies, especially in tree holes, also bridges and buildings. In summer males found at higher altitudes, females and lower altitudes. Some very large winter colonies. Lowland populations migrate farther than in the mountains [288]. Insectivore (especially aquatic) [208, 288].
Found roosting in a limestone cave [467].

Common name: Geoffroy's Bat, Geoffroy's Myotis, GEOFFROY'S MYOTIS
Notes: Flying migrant, short-distance, usually < 40 km, 105 km max in Europe [288, 250]. Refuge &/ tracking [288]. Suitable winter roosts, swarming caves [288]. Summer roosts: buildings in the north, caves and some buildings in the south. Also rocky crevices and overhangs. Winter: underground, warm temperatures. Nursery roosts, seasonal breeding [288]. Insectivore [288].

Unclear movement. Possible short distance to winter roosts [100]. Hibernation or torpor at winter roost sites. Seasonal breeding, maternity colonies. Summer roosts in buildings, sink holes, crevices, caves, hollow tress. Winter habits unknown [100], probably migrate short distances between summer and winter areas although winter range unknown [3656]. Insectivore [100].
Roosts in caves, maybe exclusively [208].

Common name: Bartel's Myotis, Hodgson's Bat, Hodgson's Myotis
Notes: Unclear movement. Roost switch, unknown extent [208]. Roost in foliage. Hibernate in caves [208].
Roosts in hollow trees, holes in thistle stems, palm-thatched roofs, coiled leaves [356].
Roosts inside bamboo [208], also houses, caves, rock cracks [465]. Form breeding colonies [465].
Roosts in limestone caves in small colonies [469].
Roosts in small colonies [167]. Insectivore [167].

Flying migrant. Cave dispersal and recongregation [100]. Refuge [100]. Few caves (~9) suitable for winter hibernation [100]. Migrate in September >100 km to hibernation caves, emerge in March/April. Maternity colonies in warm caves, form in May, disperse in July [100]. Insectivore [100].

Common name: Hasselt's Large-footed Myotis, Lesser Large-footed Bat, Lesser Large-footed Myotis, Lesser Large-tooth Bat, The Brown Bat, Van Hasselt's Bat
Notes: Found roosting in caves. Forages over water [200]. Also roosts in cracks in tree trunks, bamboo. Seemingly seasonal breeding but no nursery colonies [420]. Insectivore [420], possibly piscivore [145].

Common name: Common Asiatic Myotis, Horsfield's Bat, Horsfield's Myotis, Lesser Large-tooth Bat
Notes: Roosts in crevices, caves [200], tunnels, buildings, bridges, foliage, near water [208, 420].

Common name: Ikonnikov's Bat, Ikonnikov's Myotis, Ikonnikov's Whiskered Bat
Notes: Found hibernating in a cave [208].
Central America: Roosts in limestone caves, maybe hollow trees. Seasonal breeding, wet season [356].
Roosts in caves and trees. Hibernates in colonies. Separate maternity roosts [100], ADW: Makes small-scale movements but does not migrate. Insectivore [100].
Found in caves [208].

Non-migratory [100]. Hibernates in caves and mines. Seasonal breeding and molt (sex-segregated). Maternity colonies. Some bats found in the summer within 20 km of winter roost [100]. Insectivore [100].
Roosts in large colonies [191].
Roosts in caves. Large colonies [208, 420]. Seemingly seasonal breeding [420].

Common name: Little Brown Bat, Little Brown Myotis
Notes: Flying migrant. Caves [100]. Refuge [100]. Extent unclear: up to 100 miles [475], or up to 1000 km [100]. Suitable winter roosts: under-ground caves or old mines [100]. Migrate up to 1000 km between winter and summer roosts. Seasonal breeding, timing varies with latitude and altitude. Nursery colonies with roost fidelity. [100]. Insectivore [100].
Found in caves and man-made structures. Roosts near to water. Distinct summer and winter roosts [472]. Insectivore [472].

Roost in caves, mines, tree hollows, under bridges, buildings, foliage. Southern populations: hibernate, seasonal breeding, distinct winter roosts. Middle latitudes: two breeding seasons. Northern Queensland: nonseasonal breeding, up to three births per year [134]. Insectivore [134].

Common name: Pallid Large-footed Myotis, Philippine Large-footed Myotis
Notes: Roosts in caves, small groups [219]. Unknown, possibly piscivore [219, 145].
Roosts in caves, tunnel, mines, under bridges, rock overhangs, buildings, foliage. Three births/year [473]. Insectivore (aquatic), piscivore [473].

Common name: Burmese Whiskered Bat, Burmese Whiskered Myotis, Large Brown Myotis
Notes: Found swarming near rocky crevices [420].

Common name: Nepalese Whiskered Bat, Nepalese Whiskered Myotis, Whiskered Myotis
Notes: Roosts in banana leaves, and caves [200, 208, 219, 420]. Pakistan: hibernate, may move to rock caverns [132]. Probably  insectivore [132].

Common name: Greater Mouse-eared Bat, Large Mouse-eared Bat, Mouse-eared Bat, Mouse-eared Myotis
Notes: Flying migrant, short-distance, 50-100 km. Avg: male 27.5 km, female 51.3 km. Max 436 km. Cave congregation and dispersal [288, 250]. Refuge &/ tracking [288]. Suitable winter roosts, swarming caves [288]. Some individuals remain near winter roost year-round [250]. Nursery roosts: buildings, bridges, caves. Male summer roosts, solitary: roof spaces, shutters, tree holes, bridges, mines, caves. Winter roosts: cave, mines, bunkers, mountain cellars, warm and damp. Nursery roost fidelity. Swarming caves [288]. Insectivore [288].

Common name: Whiskered Bat, Whiskered Myotis, WHISKERED MYOTIS
Notes: Flying migrant, short-range: < 50 - 100 km movements. Four flights over 150km, max 625 km [288, 250]. Refuge [288]. Suitable winter roosts [288]. Some individuals in Finland only move 1 km between summer and winter roosts [250]. Summer roosts: cracks in houses, shutters, tree bark. Balkans: nursery roosts in bridges. Seasonal nursery roosts. Winter roosts in caves, mines, mountain cellars, hibernates often individually [288]. Insectivore [288].

Flying migrant, short-distance, usually < 40 km, 266-327 km recorded. Swarming cave distances 20-60 km. Cave congregation and dispersal [288]. Refuge, maybe also tracking [288]. Suitable winter roosts, swarming caves [288]. Summer roosts: tree holes, buildings, rock crevices, caves. Winter roosts: rock crevices, caves, mountain cellars. Congregate in large caves for winter. Swarming caves. Usually hunting grounds within 4 km of roost [288]. Insectivore [288].

Central America: Roosts in caves, hollow trees, attics. Nursery roosts [356]. South America: Roost in sheltered locations. Nursery colonies. Year round breeding, 2-3 births per year, peaks timed with insect abundance [191]. Insectivore [356].
Insectivore [208].
Maternity colonies found in buildings. Some found hibernating in mines in California and northern Mexico [474].

Common name: Singaporese Whiskered Myotis, Singapore Whiskered Bat

Notes: Roosts in caves, empty houses. Seasonal breeding [476].
Found roosting in caves [208].

Common name: Rickett's Big-footed Bat, Rickett's Big-footed Myotis
Notes: Probably roosts in caves [200]. piscivore, insectivore (aquatic) [200, 208].
Insectivore [477].
Roosts in tree holes [478].

Common name: Felten's Myotis, Maghrebian Myotis, MAGHREBIAN MYOTIS, MAGHREB MOUSE-EARED BAT
Notes: Non-migratory, max distance 22 km [288]. Nursery roosts in caves. Single roosts in tunnels, ruins, roofs, bridges. Seasonal breeding [288]. Insectivore [288].
Roosts in caves, fallen logs, under rocks [200].
Roosts in houses, hollow trees, and bamboo [200].

Migratory [3657], None observed [100]. Refuge? [3657]. Hibernation areas [3657]. Hibernate in caves throughout their range. Seasonal breeding, nursery roosts in trees and buildings [100], Travel up to 56km from summer area to winter hibernation areas [3657]. Insectivore [100].

Common name: Mandelli's Mouse-eared Bat, Mandelli's Mouse-eared Myotis
Himalayan Whiskered Bat, Himalayan Whiskered Myotis, Siliguri Bat, Small-toothed Myotis
Notes: Found roosting in caves [200, 208], rock crack [219]. Seemingly seasonal reproduction [420]. Insectivore [208].
Found roosting in a tree [190].

Common name: Indiana Bat, Indiana Myotis, Social Bat
Notes: Flying migrant. Patterns unclear [100]. Three max distances: 575, 476, 465 km [510]. Refuge, sex-biased [100]. Limestone hibernation caves. Cool, high humidity [100]. Evidence of sex-segregated migration. Females migrate to nursery roosts while males disperse around hibernation cave [100]. Two summer roosts found in Maryland of bats which hibernate in Pennsylvania [418]. Some bats migrate from Michigan to Indiana and Kentucky. Individuals from a given maternity roost sometimes use different hibernacula, don't stay grouped; seems that maternity roost fidelity is strong, but hibernacula fidelity is less [510]. Insectivore [100].
Roost in caves. Seemingly seasonal breeding [161].

Unclear movement. Possible N-S &/altitudinal migration [100, 356]. Seasonal breeding. Maternity colonies from April to September. Probably hibernates [100]. Thought to migrate, but winter behavior and locations unknown [120]. Roosts in caves, mines, buildings. Sex-segregated in the summer. Northern populations thought to migrate south to unknown location [356]. Insectivore [100].
Unclear movement, cave switching of unknown extent [102]. Roosts in caves. Cave-dependent. Distinct hibernacula and summer maternity roosts [102]. Insectivore [102].

Flying migrant, possible N-S, altitudinal migration [100]. Refuge [100]. Populations in Kansas and Texas are year-round residents, hibernating in local caves [100]. Roosts in caves. Seasonal, sex-segregated molt. Nursery roosts [100]. Insectivore [100].
Roosts in caves and crevices. Seemingly seasonal breeding [481]. Carnivore (crustaceans, fish) [481].

Unclear movement, possible short range migration [100]. Roost in crevices, caves, buildings, trees. Hibernate in caves and mines. Seasonal breeding [100]. Nursery colonies break up in the fall, but winter behavior is unknown [120]. Insectivore [100].
Found in banana leaves, a cave [102]. Insectivore [102].
Roosts in tree hollows [482].

Unclear movement [100]. Summer roosts in buildings, bridges, crevices, caves, old swallow nests. Probably move to cool mines for hibernation but sites unknown. Maternity roosts, scattered males [100]. Insectivore [100].
Roost in tree hollows [208]. Insectivore [208].

Common name: Azorean Bat, AZOREAN BAT, Azores Noctule
Notes: Roosts in and on buildings [288]. Insectivore [288].
Roosts in tree hollows. Found hibernating in a building [483].

Flying migrant, extent and patterns unclear, possibly N-S [288]. Unclear motivation, sex-biased. Found roosting in tree holes, roofs, caves. Nursery colonies, seasonal breeding. Greece: only males found in the summer, females arrive in autumn [288]. Belarus and Ukraine populations seem migratory, present from April to November [240]. Insectivore, carnivore (migratory birds) [288].

Flying migrant, long-distance. Max recorded 1,567 km, southwest-northeast. Females travel farther [288, 250]. Refuge, sex-biased [288]. Populations in Britain, some islands, Iberian peninsula sedentary [288]. Roosts in trees. Winter roosts in trees and buildings. Nursery colonies. Males stay in winter and transit regions. Hibernates [288]. Insectivore [288].

Flying migrant, autumn migration to southwest, spring migration to northeast. Usually <1,000 km, max 1,546 km. N-S, reproduction-winter/ mating [288]. Refuge. Populations in Britain and Sweden seem sedentary. Some sedentary males [288]. Roosts in buildings and tree hollows. Maternity colonies in summer, seasonal breeding [208]. Europe: Summer roosts in woodpecker holes, other tree hollows. Nursery roosts in the south use buildings. Nursery roost in Bulgaria cave. Males roost in tree holes, rock crevices, caves, buildings. Winter roosts: thick-walled tree holes, buildings, rock crevices, caves. Hibernate. Hunting distances up to 2.5 km, frequent roost change up to 12 km [288]. Insectivore [208, 288].
Hibernates in November. Seasonal breeding [208].
Roosts in crevices in trees, houses. South Africa: seasonal breeding [102]. Insectivore [102].

Flying migrant, females N-S, and young south [100]. 547 km distance observed [145]. Refuge, sex-biased [100]. Males stay in the south [100]. Roosts in tree hollows and cavities, under bark, in buildings [145]. Females and young migrate 100s miles south in the winter. Maternity colonies in hollow trees, buildings, April-August. Seasonal breeding, birth in June [100]. Insectivore [100].
Roost under bark of melaleuca trees. Seasonal breeding in the west season [134]. Insectivore [134].

Unclear movement, possible dispersal re-congregation movement but not around cave [134]. Australia: roosts in tree hollows, roofs, foliafe, under bark, among epiphytes. Seasonal breeding: mid-summer [243, 134]. Seasonal roost changes from interior rainforest in the summer to edge regions in the winter [134]. Insectivore [134].

Non-migratory [134]. Roost in dead trees, under bark or in hollows. Also buildings, bird nests. Hibernate in temperate regions. Seasonal breeding. Frequent roost shifts within a given region [134]. Insectivore [134].
Roosts in tree hollows, under bark, roofs. Maternity roosts usually in tree hollows. Hibernate. Seasonal breeding [134]. Insectivore [134].

Common name: Sunda Long-eared Bat, Sundan Long-eared Bat
Notes: Lives in small colonies [484].

Common name: New Guinea Long-eared Bat, Papuan Long-eared Bat, Small-eared Nyctophilus
Notes: Found in bamboo [243].
Probably roost in tree crevices and uner back. Females probably form seasonal maternity colonies. [134].
Probably roosts in tree hollows [243], under bark, in crevices [134]. Seasonal breeding [134]. Insectivore [134].
Roost in dead palm fronds. Seemingly seasonal breeding [134]. Insectivore [134].

Common name: Desert Long-eared Bat, Hemprich's Long-eared Bat
Notes: Roosts in cliffs and sometimes cracks around buildings. Nursery roosts, changed every 1-2 days [288]. Insectivore, possibly carnivore [288].

Common name: New Guinea Big-eared Bat, Thomas's Big-eared Bat
Notes: Probably extinct [243].
Roosts in hollow trees [200, 243].

Common name: Gilded Groove-toothed Bat, Groove-toothed Bat, Groove-toothed Trumpet-eared Bat
Notes: Found roosting in old birds nests [200].

Common name: Common Trumpet-eared Bat, Peters's Trumpet-eared Bat, Peter's Trumpet-eared Bat

Notes: Found roosting in caves [161], palm foliage, houses [243], bird nests [134]. Australia: nightly movements usually within 2 km. Maternity roosts, seasonal breeding. Sexually dimorphic: females larger [134]. Insectivore (mostly spiders actually) [134].
Roosts in and around buildings [208]. Insectivore [208].

Common name: Adams's Pipistrelle, Cape York Pipistrelle, Forest Pipistrelle
Notes: Probably roosts in trees [134]. Insectivore [134].

Common name: Mount Gargues Pipistrelle, Mt. Gargues Pipistrelle

Notes: Roosts in caves [208].
Insectivore [102].
Found in caves [161], dry bamboo [243].

Common name: Cadorna's Pipistrelle, Cadornas Pipistrelle, Thomas's Pipistrelle

Notes: Roosts under bark, aloe leaves, house roofs [102]. Insectivore [102].
Roosts in buildings, caves, tree holes, wells. Seasonal breeding [208, 420]. Inactive and partial torpid in cold and wet seasons [420]. Insectivore [208].
Roost in tree hollows. Seemingly seasonal reproduction [243].

Common name: Coromandel Pipistrelle, Indian Pipistrelle, Little Indian Bat
Notes: Roosts under bark, in trees, buildings [200, 208]. Sometimes multiple breeding seasons dependent on locality [208]. Hibernates in Pakistan [132]. Insectivore [420].
Roosts in palm trees and buildings [489].
Roosts in tree hollows. Once found roosting in a cave [491].
Roost in rock cracks, under bark [102]. Insectivore [102].
Flying migrant. N-S [120]. Refuge [120]. Some may hibernate without migrating [120]. Hibernate in colder regions [120]. Insectivore [100].
Found in banana leaves [496].
Roosts in treeferns, fallen logs, caves, urban regions [200].

Non-migratory [288]. Maximum seasonal movements of 5 km observed [250]. Nursery roosts in cliffs, building gaps. Sometimes roost in bird nests, tree holes. Winter roosts in buildings, rock crevices. Swarming at the end of August. Hibernation, though active on warm days [288]. Insectivore [288].

Non-migratory. Maximum distance observed: 2 km [288, 250]. Nursery roosts in building gaps. Roosts in rock crevices, crevices in bridges, walls, trees. Seasonal breeding. Active year-round in suitable weather [288]. Insectivore [288].
Roosts under roofs, bark [416]. Insectivore [102].

Non-migratory, very restricted range [134]. Roosts in tree hollows, under bark, between fronds. Females, but not males, often torpor in July-October for the dry season. Seasonal breeding [134]. Insectivore [134].
Roost in banana leaves and other foliage, roofs. Southern Africa: seasonal breeding. Males solitary except mating season. Females form maternity roosts [102]. Insectivore [102].

Flying migrant, long distance: max 1,905 km [509]. Mostly southwest in autumn, northeast in spring, females move south first [288]. Refuge [288]. Some males seem not to migrate. A few populations of sedentary or short-distance migratory bats observed in southern Germany, Switzerland, northern Italy  [509]. Nursery roosts mostly in the north, lowlands in trees, buildings. Mating roosts in trees, buildings bridges. Winter roosts in tree holes and wood piles, also crevices in buildings and cliffs singly or in small groups. Hibernate [288, 509]. Males tend to migrate farther, mean difference ~150 km, but more females observed migrating. Mating roosts along migration routes [509]. Insectivore [288].
Roosts in coconut palms [161, 243].
Roosts in tree stumps, thatched roofs [200].

Unclear movement. Seasonal roost shifts usually of < 10-20 km. Longest 1, 123 km [250]. Roost in buildings, sometimes rock crevices, tree bark. Hibernate in buildings, sometimes rock crevices and caves. Nursery roosts changed individually up to 15 km, entire colony up to1.3 km. Swarming roosts up to 22.5 km.
